"""
mkt-context — Proverbs 4–6 (85 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-4-6.py
Ch4: Father-instruction genre (ANE parallels: Amenemope, Ptahhotep); two-way motif = Ps 1 / Deut 30;
  personified wisdom begins (v6-9) → full development in ch8; 'guard the heart' (v23) = center of 1-9.
Ch5: 'Zarah' debate (foreign woman / prostitute / apostasy symbol); cistern/well = Song 4:12-15;
  divine surveillance (v21) = Ps 139.
Ch6: Suretyship in ANE economy; ant = ANE wisdom-nature examples; seven abominations = n/n+1 genre;
  lamp/light (v23) = Ps 119:105.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The father-instruction genre has deep ANE parallels: Egyptian wisdom texts (the Instructions of Ptahhotep, c.2400 BCE; the Instruction of Any, c.1300 BCE; the Instruction of Amenemope, c.1200 BCE) all use the 'my son' address from a senior sage to a junior. The plural 'children' here suggests the broader scribal-school context: Proverbs likely functioned both as family and as institutional wisdom education in ancient Israel, as in Egypt and Mesopotamia.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The pairing of <em>leqaḥ</em> (received instruction) and <em>tôrāh</em> (teaching/instruction) bridges the wisdom tradition and the Mosaic tradition: by the time of Sirach (Ben Sira 24:23) the identification of Wisdom with Torah is explicit. Proverbs anticipates this convergence by using Torah vocabulary for wisdom instruction.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The three-generation chain (grandfather → father → son) reflects Deuteronomy 6:4-9's mandate for intergenerational transmission of covenant knowledge. The father's recollection of his own childhood instruction models what he is now doing for his son: wisdom is passed not through texts alone but through remembered personal relationships.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Let your heart hold fast my words' — the language of holding fast (<em>ḥāzaq</em>) is covenantal: Deut 10:20 ('Hold fast to him'); Deut 30:20 ('Loving the LORD your God, obeying his voice, and holding fast to him is your life'). Wisdom instruction borrows the covenant's adhesion-language.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Wisdom as something acquired (<em>qānāh</em> = buy/get) reflects the economic intelligence of the wisdom tradition: wisdom has exchange value, not just intrinsic value. Prov 23:23 makes the commercial metaphor explicit: 'Buy truth and do not sell it — wisdom, instruction, and understanding.' The market metaphor dignifies wisdom by treating it as a scarce and valuable commodity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Wisdom as a guardian-companion begins here (v6: 'she will keep you') and develops through chs. 1-9 toward the climactic self-revelation of Woman Wisdom in ch8. The companion-guardian motif has Egyptian precedent in the <em>ma'at</em> figure — the goddess of cosmic order — whose maintenance of order protects the wise person. Proverbs demythologizes the concept while retaining its protective function.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The paradoxical opening ('the beginning of wisdom is: get wisdom') is a wisdom-school formula for the priority of wisdom over all other acquisitions. A similar saying occurs in the Egyptian Instruction of Amenemope: 'It is good to be wise; wealth is good only with wisdom.' The Israelite version grounds the priority in YHWH's nature rather than cosmic order.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The exalt-wisdom → wisdom-exalts-you reciprocity belongs to the ANE patron-client dynamic transferred to the wisdom relationship: honor the sage/wisdom and receive honor in return. The same dynamic governs Proverbs' view of honoring parents (Exod 20:12: honor your parents → long life) — relational honor is intrinsically generative.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Wisdom's garland and crown parallel the crown of the warrior and the wreath of the athlete. In the Hellenistic period, the philosopher's crown of wisdom competed with the military crown as the highest honor; Paul uses the athletic-crown metaphor in 1 Cor 9:25. The Proverbs image is the ANE antecedent: wisdom gives the most durable of all honors.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Long life as the reward of wisdom — the Deuteronomic connection is explicit: Deut 5:33 ('you may live and it may go well with you, and you may live long in the land'); the conditional promise of long life for covenant obedience is one of the pillars of Deuteronomic theology. Proverbs applies the same promise to wisdom-reception, since wisdom is the internalized form of Torah-obedience.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The path-metaphor for the moral life is ubiquitous in wisdom literature across the ANE. The Egyptian concept of <em>ma'at</em> (truth/justice/right order) was figured as a path; the Mesopotamian wisdom text <em>Ludlul bel nemeqi</em> uses path-imagery for the righteous life. Proverbs' two-path framework (righteous path/wicked path) corresponds to Psalm 1's two-way structure.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Your step will not be cramped/hampered' — the contrast with the stumbling of v19 creates the antithetical two-path structure. The image of unimpeded walking as the fruit of wisdom connects to Isa 40:31 (those who wait for the LORD will walk and not faint) and the broader biblical imagery of the LORD as a guide who makes straight paths (Ps 27:11; Isa 26:7).</p>",
    "13": "<p>'She is your life' — the identification of wisdom with life itself is the foundation of John's identification of the Logos with life (John 1:4: 'in him was life'). The wisdom tradition's life-identification was the theological soil in which the NT's Christological wisdom-identification grew; see 1 Cor 1:30 (Christ is our wisdom) and Col 2:3 (all the treasures of wisdom are in Christ).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The prohibitions in vv14-15 (do not enter, do not walk, turn away, pass on) echo the Deuteronomic prohibitions on association with Canaanites and their practices (Deut 7:2-5). The two-way framework in Proverbs carries the covenant's boundary-markers into the domain of practical ethics.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The fourfold avoidance command (shun, do not travel, turn away, pass on) has the structure of a Deuteronomic prohibition — comprehensive, leaving no ambiguity about the scope of the command. Compare Deut 12:30: 'be careful that you are not ensnared to follow them after they are destroyed before you.' Moral avoidance is a complete withdrawal, not partial distance.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The portrait of the compulsively wicked (who cannot sleep unless they do evil) has an echo in Mic 2:1: 'Woe to those who devise wickedness and work evil on their beds!' The night that should be rest becomes a time of plotting — the inversion of the righteous person's peaceful sleep (Ps 4:8: 'in peace I will both lie down and sleep').</p>",
    "17": "<p>'The bread of wickedness' and 'the wine of violence' — the dietary metaphor for moral vice is not unique to Proverbs; Amos 6:4-6 condemns those who feast while unconcerned about Israel's ruin; the connection between how you eat and what you value is a recurring prophetic-wisdom theme. The wicked are nourished by wickedness the way the righteous are nourished by wisdom (9:5).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The path of the righteous brightening to midday has a canonical counterpart in Isa 58:8 ('then your light will break forth like the dawn') and Isa 9:2 ('the people walking in darkness have seen a great light'). The wisdom tradition's light-imagery flows into the prophetic tradition and ultimately into the NT's light-of-the-world language (John 8:12; Matt 5:14).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Deep darkness (<em>'ăpēlāh</em>) as the wicked person's path is the same darkness-vocabulary used in Exod 10:22 for the plague of darkness and in Amos 5:20 ('the day of the LORD will be darkness, not light'). The moral and eschatological dimensions of darkness overlap: the wicked path is both present ignorance and future judgment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The ear-turning command ('incline your ear') is the formal address-gesture of the wisdom school and of prophetic proclamation. Isa 55:3: 'Incline your ear and come to me; hear, that your soul may live'; the same receptive posture is required for both wisdom and covenant. Proverbs and Isaiah share the conviction that hearing requires active orientation of the whole self.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Let them not escape from your eyes; keep them in the center of your heart' — the internalization of instruction through continuous attention echoes the Shema's application: Deut 6:6-8 ('these words shall be on your heart; you shall bind them as a sign on your hand; they shall be as frontlets between your eyes'). The tefillin practice externalizes what Proverbs describes as internal keeping.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Life and healing to all their flesh' (<em>ḥayyîm... marpe'</em>) — Proverbs connects wisdom reception to physical wellbeing (3:8: 'it will be healing to your flesh and refreshment to your bones'). This psychosomatic connection is more than metaphor in the ancient world; see Ps 103:3-4 (YHWH heals diseases as well as iniquities). The NT develops this in the healing ministry of Christ as wisdom incarnate.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Guard your heart above all else, for it is the source from which life flows' — the heart as the center of the moral and cognitive life in Hebrew anthropology differs from modern Western psychology: the heart is not primarily the seat of emotion but of will, intention, and decision. Jer 17:9 ('the heart is deceitful above all things') represents the prophetic diagnostic of the unregenerate heart. The NT's 'heart' transformation (Ezek 36:26; Jer 31:33) is the eschatological response to what Proverbs diagnoses as requiring vigilant guarding.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Crooked/perverse speech as the expression of the corrupted heart (v23) — Matt 15:11 makes the Proverbs logic explicit: 'it is not what goes into the mouth that defiles a person, but what comes out of the mouth; this defiles a person'; the heart that speaks crooked things is the defiled heart. Jesus cites the heart-speech connection as the core of defilement-purity.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Direct gaze as an expression of single-mindedness — the eyes that look straight ahead and do not wander are the complement of the heart that is guarded. Matt 6:22-23 ('the eye is the lamp of the body; if your eye is healthy, your whole body will be full of light') develops this connection between eye-discipline and inner moral state.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Level the path of your feet' — Isa 26:7: 'The path of the righteous is level; you make smooth the way of the righteous.' The leveling of the path is both a divine action (YHWH smooths the way) and a human responsibility (the wise person weighs/levels before acting). The interplay of divine provision and human wisdom-work is characteristic of the biblical understanding of providence.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Do not swerve right or left' — Deut 5:32: 'You shall be careful to do as the LORD your God commanded you. You shall not turn aside to the right hand or to the left'; Josh 1:7: 'Be careful to obey all the law my servant Moses gave you; do not turn from it to the right or to the left.' The two-path wisdom vocabulary is drawn directly from the Deuteronomic framework for covenant faithfulness.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 5 is the first of three extended warnings against the 'foreign/strange woman' (chs. 5, 6:20-35, 7). The genre corresponds to warnings in Egyptian wisdom: the Instruction of Any warns, 'be on your guard against a woman from abroad, who is not known in her town.' The ANE concern is broadly shared: the foreign woman represents danger to the household and its economic stability.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Discretion (<em>mĕzimmôt</em>) and knowledge (<em>da'at</em>) are the specific wisdom-qualities threatened by the foreign woman. The wisdom school's purpose is to produce the kind of discernment that identifies and resists the seductive speech described in v3; this chapter can be read as a practical wisdom-school exercise in applied discrimination.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The 'strange/foreign woman' (<em>zārāh</em>) is one of the most debated figures in Proverbs scholarship. Three interpretations have been offered: (1) a literal foreign woman (representing the apostasy danger of Deut 7:3-4); (2) a prostitute or adulteress (the most common reading); (3) a metaphor for Lady Folly, the foil to Lady Wisdom of ch8-9. All three may be simultaneously in view: the text is deliberately multi-layered.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The bitter-end contrast with the honeyed beginning is a well-established wisdom teaching on deceptive appearances. The Egyptian Instruction of Ankhsheshonq: 'Beautiful is a woman whose words are sweet, but her interior is bitter poison.' The wisdom tradition across the ANE recognized that pleasure leading to destruction is more dangerous than direct adversity.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Her feet going down to death and Sheol connects to the underworld geography of the ancient Near East: the dead descend to the realm below. Prov 2:18-19 makes the same point; 7:27 climaxes it: 'her house is the way to Sheol, going down to the chambers of death.' The foreign woman is mapped onto the descent-to-death spatial imagery of the underworld.</p>",
    "6": "<p>She does not ponder the path of life — the <em>peles</em> (weighing/balance) imagery links her to the section's broader concern with measured, examined paths (4:26). The chaotic, unmeasured quality of her paths is the opposite of the wise person's deliberate, examined way of living.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The father returns to the plural 'sons' (as in 4:1) — signaling either a school-address or a deliberate universalizing of the warning. The instruction is not private but communal; wisdom is transmitted through communities of practice, not solitary learning.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Distance rather than resistance — 'keep your way far from her' — is the wisdom strategy. Compare Joseph's flight from Potiphar's wife (Gen 39:12: 'he left his garment in her hand and fled and got out of the house'). Physical distance is the wisest first response to sexual temptation; the wisdom tradition consistently commends avoidance over confrontation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Honor, years, and strength given to the 'others' — the economic devastation of adultery connects to the broader wisdom concern with household management. Prov 6:26 returns to the cost-accounting: the adultery transaction costs a man's precious life. The wisdom tradition treats sexual fidelity as integral to economic stewardship.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The 'strangers' (<em>zārîm</em>) who benefit from the adulterer's loss are the very 'foreignness' the word <em>zārāh</em> (strange woman) connotes: by going to the foreign woman, the fool enriches foreigners with what should have stayed in the household. The word-play reinforces the structural irony.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The groaning-at-the-end (v11-14) is a wisdom genre: the retrospective regret speech that inverts the initial seduction. This genre teaches through negative example: by imagining the speaker's regret, the student is warned not to take the path that leads there. Ben Sira (Sirach 5:7-8; 18:24-25) develops the same genre of prospective regret-avoidance.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'I hated discipline' — the retrospective voice identifies the root of the failure: not weakness in the face of temptation but the prior rejection of correction. Prov 15:32: 'whoever ignores instruction despises himself.' The wisdom tradition consistently treats the rejection of correction as the primary cause of moral catastrophe.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The teachers (<em>môrāy</em>) and instructors (<em>mĕlamĕdāy</em>) of v13 confirm the school-context of Proverbs' wisdom transmission. The regret is social as well as personal: the failed student brings shame to the community of teachers who invested in him. Ben Sira 11:28: 'call no one blessed before his death; a man is known by how he ends.'</p>",
    "14": "<p>'In the midst of the assembly and congregation' — the communal setting of disgrace connects to the covenant assembly (<em>qāhāl</em>, <em>'ēdāh</em>). These are the terms used for Israel's covenant gathering (Num 16:3; Deut 9:10; 31:30); to be shamed 'in the congregation' is to be exposed before the covenant community. Sexual dishonor has public, covenantal dimensions in Israel.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Drink water from your own cistern' — the source-imagery for the marriage relationship has ANE parallels. The Egyptian love poetry of the Chester Beatty papyri uses water and garden imagery for the beloved. More directly, Song of Solomon 4:12-15 uses the 'locked garden,' 'sealed fountain,' and 'springs of water' for the beloved wife — imagery structurally parallel to Proverbs 5:15-18. Both texts draw on a shared reservoir of ANE erotic imagery.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The rhetorical question about springs going public (<em>ḥûṣāh</em> = outside/in the streets) addresses the logic of fidelity: the water that belongs to the household does not spread to public channels. The wisdom tradition treats marital sexuality as household-proprietary — not merely personal preference but economic and social boundary-maintenance.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'For you alone' (<em>lĕbaddĕkā</em>) — the exclusivity principle that grounds marriage covenant. The covenant vocabulary of exclusivity — 'you shall have no other gods before me' (Exod 20:3) — has its domestic analogue in marital fidelity. The Hosea-YHWH/Israel marriage metaphor (Hos 1-3) shows how thoroughly the OT interweaves covenant and marriage logic.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Wife of your youth' (<em>ēšet nĕ'ûreḵā</em>) — the youth-marriage ideal appears also in Mal 2:14-15: 'the LORD was witness between you and the wife of your youth... she is your companion and the wife of your covenant.' Malachi's condemnation of divorce uses the same vocabulary; both Proverbs and Malachi ground marital fidelity in the original covenant commitment of youth.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The explicit erotic language of v19 (breasts, satisfaction, ravished) stands in the tradition of explicit sexual celebration in Song of Solomon. The wisdom tradition does not spiritualize away the physical dimension of marriage. The canon's inclusion of both Song of Solomon and Proverbs 5 affirms that sexual joy within the covenant relationship is a positive good that wisdom commends rather than merely tolerates.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Why be intoxicated (<em>šāgāh</em>) with a foreign woman?' — the intoxication/wandering verb connects to the description of the drunkard's unstable gait in Prov 23:33. Sexual infatuation and drunkenness share the same disorienting effect in wisdom's analysis: both produce wandering, stumbling, and loss of moral direction.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'For a man's ways are before the eyes of the LORD' — the divine surveillance theme has canonical parallels in Ps 139:1-4 (YHWH knows every path and thought), Job 31:4 (God watches all my steps and counts my journeys), and Jer 16:17 (YHWH's eyes are on all their ways). The omniscient divine gaze is one of wisdom's primary deterrents: nothing is private before YHWH.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'His own iniquities will trap him' — the self-entrapment principle is emphasized in the prophets: Isa 5:18 ('woe to those who draw iniquity with cords of falsehood'); Hos 5:4 ('their deeds do not permit them to return to their God; for the spirit of whoredom is within them, and they know not the LORD'). Sin creates a structural bondage that removes freedom of action over time.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'He will die for lack of discipline' — the fatal consequence of rejected wisdom forms an inclusio with v12 ('I hated discipline'). The chapter demonstrates Proverbs' central logic: wisdom offers life; its rejection leads to death. The same binary appears in Deut 30:19 ('I have set before you life and death, blessing and curse; therefore choose life').</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>Suretyship-pledging (<em>'ārab</em>) was a formal legal act in the ancient economy: the guarantor became legally responsible for another's debt. The economic risk was real and documented in ANE texts: Mesopotamian business records show numerous cases of guarantors losing their assets when debtors defaulted. Proverbs returns to this theme in 11:15; 17:18; 20:16; 22:26-27 — the repeated warnings reflect a genuine social problem.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Snared by the words of your mouth' — the legal binding power of speech is a foundational principle in ANE law: verbal contracts were enforceable. Numbers 30:2: 'if a man vows a vow to the LORD, or swears an oath to bind himself by a pledge, he shall not break his word.' Proverbs treats the suretyship pledge as a serious verbal commitment that cannot be lightly escaped.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The urgency of seeking release connects to Proverbs' practical wisdom about acting before problems compound: Prov 25:8-9 advises settling disputes quickly before going to court. The biblical wisdom tradition consistently prefers prevention and early resolution over resignation to consequences.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Give no sleep to your eyes' in a crisis — the deliberate inversion of the sluggard's excessive sleep (vv9-10) creates an implicit comparison: not all wakefulness is virtue; it depends on what the emergency demands. Wisdom is context-sensitive about the virtue of rest.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The gazelle and bird fleeing the hunter are wisdom-nature illustrations of the kind that appear throughout the ANE wisdom tradition: Amenemope compares the discerning person to various animals. The use of animal behavior as ethical illustration assumes the created order is morally instructive — a uniquely wisdom-theological claim about the coherence of creation and ethics.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The ant (<em>nĕmālāh</em>) appears in Proverbs only here and 30:25. ANE nature-observation was a form of wisdom education: Mesopotamian omen texts observed insects for predictive purposes; Egyptian wisdom used animal behavior for moral instruction. The ant's self-motivated industry without human oversight reflects the wisdom tradition's ideal of internalized, rather than externally enforced, virtue.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The ant's self-governance — no officer, no overseer — represents the highest form of Proverbs' virtue ideal: discipline that requires no external coercion. Compare Jer 31:33-34 (the new covenant: everyone will know YHWH directly, not requiring the external instruction of another). The ant prefigures the new-covenant ideal of internalized law.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The harvest-preparation pattern mirrors the agricultural cycle of the ancient Near East: summer grain harvest (April-June) and autumn fruit harvest (August-October) provided the window for food storage. The ant's behavior is empirically accurate — harvester ants do store seeds. The wisdom observation is grounded in real natural history.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The rhetorical questions to the sluggard have a structural parallel in YHWH's speeches from the whirlwind in Job 38-39: 'Where were you when I laid the foundation of the earth?' Both use unanswerable questions as pedagogical instruments. In Job, the questions expose cosmic ignorance; in Proverbs, they expose domestic negligence.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'A little sleep, a little slumber' — the triple diminishing phrase ('a little... a little... a little') is a wisdom rhetoric of accumulation through minimization. The same ironic minimization appears in Eccl 10:1: 'dead flies make the perfumer's ointment give off a stench; so a little folly outweighs wisdom and honor.' Small acts accumulate to define a life.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Poverty arriving like a traveler/vagabond is a wisdom shock-metaphor: what seems distant arrives suddenly. The same imagery in Prov 24:33-34 (the verbatim repetition of vv10-11 there confirms its status as a fixed wisdom saying). The suddenness-of-poverty image teaches the illusion of temporal distance between present negligence and future consequence.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>Bĕliyya'al</em> (worthlessness) is a term applied in the historical books to the most despicable members of Israelite society: the men of Gibeah (Judg 19:22), the sons of Eli (1 Sam 2:12), Nabal (1 Sam 25:17), and Shimei (1 Kgs 2:36-37). The word became a proper name ('Belial') in later Jewish and NT usage (2 Cor 6:15: 'What accord has Christ with Belial?').</p>",
    "13": "<p>Body-language communication of malice — winking eyes, shuffling feet, pointing fingers — is part of the wisdom tradition's sophisticated observation of non-verbal communication. The ancient Near Eastern legal and administrative context required reading body language to detect deception; wisdom education trained this perceptual skill.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Perversities in his heart' (<em>tahpukôt</em>) — the category of fundamental moral inversion appears in Deuteronomy's polemic against false prophets and corrupt leaders (Deut 32:20: 'perverse generation'). Proverbs moves the category from covenantal analysis to individual character analysis: the troublemaker's evil is a matter of distorted fundamental orientation, not just bad behavior.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The sudden, irremediable destruction of the troublemaker without 'remedy' (<em>marpē'</em> = healing/remedy) echoes the prophetic judgment-oracles: Jer 14:19 (is there no remedy/healing for us?); Isa 1:5-6 (the whole head is sick; there is no soundness from head to foot). The absence of remedy is the sign of judgment beyond ordinary repair.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The numerical saying (n/n+1 format) is a well-attested ANE wisdom genre: it appears in Ugaritic texts, in Amos 1-2 (for three transgressions, even four), in Prov 30:15,18,21,29, and in Ben Sira. The n+1 structure creates a rhetorical build-up that focuses attention on the final item: the extra item is the climactic abomination. Here, discord among brothers (v19b) is that climax.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The seven abominations list maps onto the Decalogue: lying tongue and false witness correspond to the 9th commandment (Exod 20:16); shedding innocent blood to the 6th (Exod 20:13); the list as a whole can be read as a wisdom-tradition restatement of covenant ethics in compressed form. The haughty eyes that head the list echo the warning against pride that runs through Proverbs (16:18; Isa 2:11-12).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The heart that devises wicked plans connects to the prophetic diagnosis of Jer 4:14: 'How long will you harbor your wicked thoughts?'; Mic 2:1: 'Woe to those who devise wickedness and work evil on their beds!' The heart as the origin-point of moral failure is the shared diagnosis of wisdom and prophecy.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A false witness (<em>'ēd šāqer</em>) as the penultimate abomination connects to the 9th commandment's legal context (Exod 20:16; Deut 19:16-21 on the treatment of false witnesses) and to the prophetic critique of corrupt courts (Isa 29:21; Amos 5:10-12). The climactic seventh abomination — sowing discord among brothers — is the social consequence of all the preceding individual sins.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Father's command and mother's teaching in parallel — the dual-parent authority echoes Prov 1:8; 10:1; 15:20; 23:22. The mother's <em>tôrāh</em> (instruction) is the same word as the Mosaic Torah; Proverbs consistently gives maternal wisdom the same authoritative vocabulary as paternal and Mosaic instruction. This bilateral authority was unusual in the ancient world.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Bind them on your heart' and 'tie them around your neck' — the language of physical inscription/binding parallels the tefillin command of Deut 6:8 and the mezuzah of Deut 6:9. The Deuteronomic practice externalizes through ritual what Proverbs describes as internal inscription. Both are forms of ensuring that instruction remains present and binding.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The three life-states in which wisdom guides (walking, sleeping, waking) recall the Shema's three contexts: 'when you sit in your house, when you walk by the way, when you lie down, and when you rise up' (Deut 6:7). Proverbs appropriates the Deuteronomic all-encompassing instruction-framework for wisdom. Wisdom becomes the functionally omnipresent guide that the Shema envisions for covenant instruction.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'The command is a lamp and the teaching is a light' — Ps 119:105: 'Your word is a lamp to my feet and a light to my path.' The lamp-light imagery for divine instruction is shared between Proverbs and the psalms; both draw on the ancient Near Eastern motif of the god as light-guide. Proverbs specifically connects the lamp to the instruction that 'disciplines' (<em>mûsār</em>), making the light of Torah the instrument of moral correction.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The evil woman (<em>'ēšet rā'</em>) and the foreign woman (<em>nĕkrîyyāh</em>) in v24 may specifically allude to the Deuteronomic foreign-wife prohibition (Deut 7:3-4): don't intermarry with the nations, 'for they would turn away your sons from following me to serve other gods.' The foreign woman's seductive speech threatens covenant faithfulness, not just personal morality.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Do not desire her beauty' — the 10th commandment's prohibition on coveting (Exod 20:17; Deut 5:21) extends to the prohibition of desire before action. Wisdom's treatment of adulterous desire as the commandment's target pre-empts the action by addressing the internal state; Jesus in Matt 5:28 applies the same logic explicitly: 'everyone who looks at a woman with lustful intent has already committed adultery with her in his heart.'</p>",
    "26": "<p>The economic assessment of adultery — harlot's price = a loaf of bread vs. adultery costs your life — reflects the ancient Near Eastern legal reality: adultery with a married woman was a capital crime (Lev 20:10; Deut 22:22) while prostitution, though dishonored, was not. The wisdom calculus is hard-edged: the stakes are categorically different.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The fire-in-the-bosom metaphor echoes the broader biblical use of fire for divine judgment and human passion: Song 8:6 ('jealousy is fierce as the grave; its flashes are flashes of fire, the very flame of the LORD'). The connection between sexual passion and destructive fire is made explicit in Song 8; Proverbs uses the fire-metaphor specifically for the adultery that destroys the household.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The second fire-metaphor (hot coals under the feet) intensifies the first: fire destroys not just clothing (v27) but flesh. The escalation from clothing to flesh mirrors the legal escalation from the harlot transaction (minor loss) to adultery (capital offense, v29). The rhetorical questions lead inescapably to the comparison in v29.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'He will not go unpunished' (<em>lō' yinnāqeh</em>) — the same phrase used in Exod 34:7 for YHWH's refusal to clear the guilty. Proverbs applies the divine no-impunity principle to adultery: the offense against marriage is treated with the same categorical certainty as YHWH's treatment of covenant violation. The punishment's inevitability is the point, not its mechanism.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The thief-who-steals-from-hunger comparison sets up the adultery contrast: there is a human context in which theft is somewhat understandable (starvation), but there is no comparable context for adultery. The wisdom tradition distinguishes between mitigated and unmitigated moral wrongs in a way that parallels the legal distinction between premeditated and circumstantial offenses.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Sevenfold restitution beyond the legal requirement (Exod 22:4 mandates double) — the 'sevenfold' is probably proverbial hyperbole for complete restitution. The wisdom point is that theft carries a full compensatory penalty however mitigated the motive; the analogy then makes adultery's categorically greater offense even clearer.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'He who commits adultery lacks heart/sense (<em>ḥasar-lēb</em>)' — the wisdom tradition's diagnosis of adultery as cognitive failure, not merely moral failure, echoes the broader Proverbs pattern: folly is not primarily ignorance but the failure to apply what is known. The adulterer is not ignorant of the consequences (vv27-31 have made them clear) but lacks the wisdom-organ to integrate that knowledge with action.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'His reproach will not be wiped away' — Num 5:11-31 (the ordeal of the bitter water for suspected adultery) and Lev 20:10 (capital punishment for adultery) show the severity of adultery's legal consequences in Israelite law. The wisdom tradition's observation that the social shame of adultery outlasts any possible compensation reflects the social reality of the ancient honor-shame culture.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The jealous husband's wrath as 'messengers of death' (like the king's wrath in 16:14) — the ancient Near Eastern legal codes (the Code of Hammurabi §129; Middle Assyrian Laws §A15) gave the cuckolded husband the right of capital punishment over both parties. Proverbs does not specify the punishment but notes the inevitable violence: the husband's jealousy (<em>qin'āh</em>) is an unstoppable force.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'He will not accept any ransom' — the legal finality of the offense: money cannot compensate for adultery the way it compensates for theft. The same no-ransom principle appears in Num 35:31-34 for murder: some offenses cannot be monetized. Adultery and murder share the category of offenses that pollute the land itself (Lev 18:24-28), requiring expulsion or death rather than restitution.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(existing, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in PROVERBS.values())
    print(f'proverbs mkt-context: wrote {total} verses for ch 4–6')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
